WEBVTT

00:09.484 --> 00:13.790
<i>♪ We've come
A long, long way together ♪</i>

00:13.923 --> 00:18.127
<i>♪ Through the hard times
And the good ♪</i>

00:18.260 --> 00:22.397
<i>♪ I have to
Celebrate you, baby ♪</i>

00:22.531 --> 00:26.703
<i>♪ I have to praise you
Like I should... ♪</i>

00:35.377 --> 00:38.380
<i>Now time for the man
you've all been waiting for.</i>

00:38.513 --> 00:41.150
<i>He is the king
of the high street.</i>

00:41.283 --> 00:45.287
<i>He's the Wolfgang
Amadeus Mozart of retail.</i>

00:45.420 --> 00:48.256
<i>He's the Da Vinci
of dealmaking.</i>

00:48.390 --> 00:50.827
<i>And he's the Monet of money.</i>

00:51.894 --> 00:53.628
<i>Sir Richard McCreadie!</i>

00:59.401 --> 01:01.636
<i>Thank you very much, Caroline.</i>

01:01.771 --> 01:05.474
<i>In that wonderful Monda dress,
you look knockout.</i>

01:05.607 --> 01:08.745
<i>When I was at school, my, uh,
schoolteacher used to read us</i>

01:08.878 --> 01:11.313
<i>a fairy tale
at the end of the day.</i>

01:11.446 --> 01:12.849
<i>And my favorite fairy tale was</i>

01:12.982 --> 01:14.851
<i>"The Goose That Laid
the Golden Egg."</i>

01:14.984 --> 01:16.618
<i>That's what Monda is to me.</i>

01:16.753 --> 01:18.620
<i>Monda is the golden goose,</i>

01:18.755 --> 01:21.423
<i>and I love the eggs
that it lays.</i>

01:21.556 --> 01:24.392
<i>Tonight, we're gonna reward
the shining stars. First up,</i>

01:24.526 --> 01:26.696
<i>Distribution Team Leader
of the Year,</i>

01:26.829 --> 01:28.363
<i>and that is Amanda Conrad.</i>

01:29.999 --> 01:32.034
<i>Here's 10,000 pounds
for you to distribute.</i>

01:35.537 --> 01:36.773
<i>Lifetime Achievement Award</i>

01:36.906 --> 01:38.440
<i>goes to Philip Walker.</i>

01:40.910 --> 01:43.212
<i>I think I should've got
this one, to be honest.</i>

01:43.345 --> 01:46.215
<i>I'm sure you put a few hours
in yourself. Congratulations.</i>

01:46.348 --> 01:47.784
<i>Next is Buyer of the Year,</i>

01:47.917 --> 01:50.452
<i>for driving the hardest
bargains in the business.</i>

01:50.585 --> 01:52.221
<i>Glad I don't have
to deal with him.</i>

01:52.354 --> 01:54.223
<i>Good friend of mine,
Michael Harris.</i>

01:56.525 --> 01:59.561
<i>Well done. Well done.
Here you go.</i>

01:59.695 --> 02:03.065
<i>This year, I'm delighted
to announce</i>

02:03.298 --> 02:06.235
<i>that Monda have paid out
the biggest dividend</i>

02:06.368 --> 02:08.871
<i>that any private company
has ever paid.</i>

02:09.005 --> 02:13.676
<i>One-point-two billion pounds
to be paid to our owner</i>

02:13.810 --> 02:17.312
<i>and my very own
billion-dollar babe, Samantha.</i>

02:19.749 --> 02:22.218
<i>Um, wow, that is
a really big check.</i>

02:22.350 --> 02:24.220
<i>I don't know what to do
with all those zeros.</i>

02:24.352 --> 02:26.388
<i>But, um, I feel like
we've earned it,</i>

02:26.521 --> 02:29.859
<i>so thank you so much to Rich,
and thank you to everybody.</i>

02:29.992 --> 02:32.327
<i>You guys, you know,
you've all worked so hard,</i>

02:32.460 --> 02:34.797
<i>and this is for all of you.</i>

02:34.931 --> 02:39.302
<i>I mean... No, not literally,
but I mean, thank you.</i>

03:03.860 --> 03:05.427
Thank you.

03:07.763 --> 03:08.831
What a mess.

03:08.965 --> 03:12.268
Why did he need to build
an amphitheater?

03:12.400 --> 03:15.104
It was a crazy idea.
Too ambitious.

03:15.338 --> 03:18.373
"My name is Ozymandias,
king of kings:

03:18.506 --> 03:22.477
Look on my works,
ye Mighty, and despair!"

03:22.611 --> 03:26.015
- What?
- Oh, nothing.

03:30.887 --> 03:33.155
On Friday night
for the welcoming drinks,

03:33.388 --> 03:35.590
we are at the Jackie O' Bar.
Nice and informal.

03:35.725 --> 03:38.393
That's where Pixie Lott and
Fatboy Slim will be playing.

03:38.526 --> 03:40.428
- Oh, great. Yeah.
- Yeah. Um, on Saturday,

03:40.562 --> 03:42.164
we're going
to bring the grand piano

03:42.397 --> 03:44.399
to the Oasis Pool for Elton.

03:44.532 --> 03:47.837
Then Sunday daytime
we're going to go to the arena

03:47.970 --> 03:49.305
for the gladiator games,

03:49.437 --> 03:50.940
- as you requested.
- Yay!

03:51.073 --> 03:54.377
And Sunday night,
down by the beach, Coldplay.

04:01.951 --> 04:03.686
What's he saying?

04:05.388 --> 04:06.923
Why are you shrugging?
What's he saying?

04:07.056 --> 04:08.590
- Don't know.
- You don't know? Why?

04:08.724 --> 04:10.927
He's Bulgarian. I'm Greek.

04:11.060 --> 04:12.560
- You don't understand it?
- No.

04:12.695 --> 04:15.630
Fucking hell, Giannis, man!

04:15.765 --> 04:18.034
There is more than one type
of foreign language.

04:18.166 --> 04:21.370
I know that. I'm not an idiot.
Why are you hiring Bulgarians?

04:21.503 --> 04:23.739
They're cheap. That's why.

04:23.873 --> 04:25.975
It's slow, Giannis.
The whole lot.

04:26.108 --> 04:27.910
They never made
an amphitheater before.

04:28.044 --> 04:30.913
Yeah, I've never made an
amphitheater before, obviously.

04:32.081 --> 04:33.349
This our main beach.

04:33.481 --> 04:34.582
Yeah.

04:36.686 --> 04:38.120
Nice.

04:39.621 --> 04:40.923
Who are they?

04:41.057 --> 04:42.358
They... They are camping.

04:42.490 --> 04:44.492
What is it, Duke of Edinburgh?

04:44.626 --> 04:47.964
- Syrian refugees.
- Poor things.

04:48.097 --> 04:50.565
They've come a long way.
They won't mind going further.

04:50.700 --> 04:52.567
- Rich.
- What?

04:52.702 --> 04:53.668
They're refugees.

04:53.803 --> 04:55.805
They can find refuge somewhere

04:55.938 --> 04:58.908
that isn't smack bang in
the middle of our fucking view.

04:59.041 --> 05:01.609
In Greece, all beaches
are public.

05:01.744 --> 05:03.511
It's not me. It's my guests.

05:03.645 --> 05:05.748
Some of them are
very superficial.

05:09.651 --> 05:12.088
It's just, all I can see
is plywood, mate.

05:12.221 --> 05:14.924
I'm really anxious.
This is... It's not finished.

05:15.057 --> 05:17.393
Don't worry.
Rome wasn't built in a day.

05:17.559 --> 05:20.096
Yeah, but this is... This is
a tiny little bit of Rome,

05:20.229 --> 05:21.731
and you've had 10 days.

05:21.864 --> 05:24.266
We could make a virtue of it
being half built.

05:24.499 --> 05:26.035
The ruins
of an ancient amphitheater.

05:26.168 --> 05:27.703
No. No ruins.

05:27.837 --> 05:29.571
No ruins. Melanie, tell him why.

05:29.705 --> 05:32.274
One photo,
and it's an easy tabloid headline.

05:32.507 --> 05:35.444
The end of an empire.
Fiddling while Rome burns.

05:35.577 --> 05:37.645
- Handing it to them on a plate.
- I know.

05:37.780 --> 05:39.415
They're already
like flies on shit.

05:39.547 --> 05:41.784
Sorry. I am joking.
It will be finished.

05:41.917 --> 05:43.953
Actually, Rich, from this angle,
it looks very...

05:44.086 --> 05:45.921
- It's very imperial.
- Ohh...

05:46.055 --> 05:50.126
Those who are about to die
salute you.

05:53.628 --> 05:55.563
Go on, then. Die.

05:57.565 --> 05:59.769
I'm dying.

05:59.902 --> 06:03.973
Nah, you can die better than
that. Die again, but better.

06:09.611 --> 06:11.313
I'm dying.

06:21.690 --> 06:24.093
What's wrong with him?
Looks like a rescue cat

06:24.226 --> 06:25.828
that needs to be put down.

06:25.961 --> 06:28.097
I warned you,
they don't like being moved.

06:28.230 --> 06:29.932
It takes time
for them to settle.

06:30.066 --> 06:32.634
We've not brought him
to go on a yoga retreat.

06:32.768 --> 06:35.104
- He's supposed to be scary.
- When did you get here?

06:35.237 --> 06:37.173
Last week.
All this banging and clattering

06:37.306 --> 06:39.308
isn't helping, all right?

06:39.542 --> 06:41.143
What is this?

06:41.277 --> 06:43.946
- It's...
- It's like some sort of prison.

06:44.080 --> 06:47.049
We need something to pep him
up a bit. Some cocaine.

06:47.183 --> 06:50.352
The kitchen staff have some.
I was told.

06:50.585 --> 06:52.154
What he needs is a sedative,
if anything.

06:52.288 --> 06:54.824
- Mum!
- Oh, Nanny's here now.

06:54.957 --> 06:58.660
- She's still alive.
- Come here. Come here.

06:58.794 --> 07:01.564
- Ah, Ricky.
- Ah! All right, Finn.

07:01.697 --> 07:04.834
- Hi, Dad. Yeah, go on.
- Where's your big brother?

07:04.967 --> 07:06.502
Adrian's busy working.

07:06.634 --> 07:09.071
- He works too hard.
- He'll be here on the night.

07:09.205 --> 07:10.940
- He's a grafter, like his dad.
- Yeah.

07:11.073 --> 07:13.608
- Why have you got the lion?
- It's for the gladiator games.

07:13.742 --> 07:15.744
We're recreating <i>Gladiator,</i>
like we used to.

07:15.878 --> 07:17.813
It was tigers, not lions,
in <i>Gladiator.</i>

07:17.947 --> 07:19.849
That film was littered
with inaccuracies.

07:19.982 --> 07:21.584
Don't get me started
on <i>Gladiator.</i>

07:21.717 --> 07:23.552
We want it to be authentic.

07:23.686 --> 07:26.654
- What's his name?
- Clarence.

07:26.789 --> 07:28.157
Hiya.

07:31.827 --> 07:32.928
Schoolboy error.

07:33.062 --> 07:34.730
Never ever show fear to a lion.

07:34.864 --> 07:36.532
Lions can smell fear.

07:36.664 --> 07:39.568
I'm like that. I can smell fear.

07:39.702 --> 07:43.172
What you doing lurking around
like a tabloid hack?

07:43.305 --> 07:46.075
Uh, I'm Nick, the writer.

07:46.208 --> 07:48.177
- Your biographer.
- Yeah, I know <i>who</i> you are.

07:48.310 --> 07:50.546
I was asking
what the fuck you're doing.

07:50.679 --> 07:54.416
Rich, don't frighten Nick.
He's on your side.

07:54.649 --> 07:58.754
Thank you, Sir Richard,
for appearing before us today.

07:58.888 --> 08:00.556
I wasn't aware I had a choice.

08:00.689 --> 08:03.993
Retail fashion is
a huge global industry.

08:04.126 --> 08:05.461
In the UK alone, it's worth

08:05.694 --> 08:08.764
an estimated
60 billion pounds annually.

08:08.898 --> 08:12.034
The owner of H&M is
the richest man in Sweden.

08:12.168 --> 08:14.669
The owner of Zara is one of
the richest men in the world.

08:14.803 --> 08:16.605
You are Britain's equivalent.

08:16.739 --> 08:18.941
Famous for owning
several high-street brands,

08:19.074 --> 08:22.111
including Monda
and of course M&J.

08:22.244 --> 08:26.081
Last year, M&J went bankrupt
with the loss of 11,000 jobs.

08:26.215 --> 08:28.851
- A lot of those were part-time.
- You've been described

08:28.984 --> 08:31.854
as the unacceptable face
of capitalism. Is that fair?

08:31.987 --> 08:33.789
Have you taken a look
in the mirror?

08:35.323 --> 08:38.594
You've been described
as, uh, "Sir Greedy,"

08:38.760 --> 08:41.597
uh, "Sir Shifty,"

08:41.730 --> 08:43.164
"Greedy McCreadie."

08:43.299 --> 08:46.101
Been calls for you to be
stripped of your knighthood.

08:46.235 --> 08:48.070
Sir Richard,
what would you say to that?

08:48.204 --> 08:50.639
Envy and jealousy,
my doctor tells me,

08:50.773 --> 08:55.010
are incurable diseases.
I've done nothing wrong.

08:55.144 --> 08:56.912
Yes, you have.

08:57.046 --> 08:59.114
- Get off him, you bitch!
- Disgusting man.

08:59.248 --> 09:01.617
Do you know what you've...?
Get off!

09:01.750 --> 09:04.954
<i>I hate those shites that
try to embarrass my son in public.</i>

09:05.087 --> 09:06.722
- Scum of the earth.
- Where is my job?

09:06.855 --> 09:09.158
- Opportunistic bitch.
- Where are our jobs?

09:09.291 --> 09:11.193
How old are you, Nick?

09:11.327 --> 09:13.629
- I'm 44.
- Mm, you look...

09:13.762 --> 09:16.131
- You look half that.
- Oh, thank you very much.

09:16.265 --> 09:20.803
You have very pale skin.
Like a baby.

09:20.936 --> 09:22.104
Um, ahem, so...

09:22.238 --> 09:26.275
- So you are writing Ricky's book?
- That's right.

09:26.408 --> 09:29.111
If you're gonna write something,
make sure it's good.

09:29.245 --> 09:31.780
- Well, I'll try.
- No, you can't try.

09:31.914 --> 09:33.082
You gotta be able to do it.

09:33.215 --> 09:34.917
You either do it
or you can't do it.

09:35.050 --> 09:36.785
Can you write the book, Nick?

09:36.919 --> 09:38.454
Uh, yes. Yes, I can.

09:38.722 --> 09:39.922
- Is that a "yes" I heard?
- Yes.

09:40.055 --> 09:42.091
Yes, that's fine.

09:42.224 --> 09:45.160
My son Ricky,
he pretends that he's...

09:45.294 --> 09:47.029
He's... You know,
he's cocky and loud

09:47.162 --> 09:49.131
and all of that stuff,
but he isn't really.

09:49.265 --> 09:51.300
He's very sensitive,
very, very shy.

09:51.433 --> 09:54.370
Very shy little boy, he was,
when he was at school, you know.

09:54.503 --> 09:56.272
<i>Much more sensitive
than people think.</i>

09:56.405 --> 09:58.742
<i>You know, he hides it
with all his bluster.</i>

09:58.874 --> 10:01.711
Roll up for the amazing
Señor Ricardo, aka Tricky Dicky.

10:01.844 --> 10:04.813
Have you got a coin, Lewis, that
I could borrow for this trick?

10:04.947 --> 10:07.983
Thank you very much.
Oh, we have 50 English pence.

10:08.117 --> 10:09.785
Big spender.
Now, watch carefully.

10:09.918 --> 10:12.554
Well, as carefully as you can
with your rubbish eyes,

10:12.788 --> 10:14.724
as I make your coin...

10:14.857 --> 10:16.058
disappear.

10:16.191 --> 10:17.259
- Yeah!
- Watch again

10:17.393 --> 10:18.861
as I weave another spell,

10:18.994 --> 10:20.562
make it come back. You ready?

10:21.864 --> 10:23.198
You're up, Greedy.

10:23.332 --> 10:24.900
Ah, shit. Sorry, Lewis.

10:25.034 --> 10:26.402
I guess
your coin's gone forever.

10:26.535 --> 10:29.238
- Hey, that was my 50p.
- It's vanished into the ether.

10:29.371 --> 10:32.975
There's a very fine line
between magic and tragic.

10:33.108 --> 10:36.746
Always makes me laugh how
everyone always thinks of him

10:36.879 --> 10:40.316
as this sort of barrow boy, just
because he left school at 16,

10:40.449 --> 10:43.152
but, heh, it was
a private school.

10:43.285 --> 10:45.722
You know? And the two of us,
we hated it.

10:45.854 --> 10:47.856
Run, McCreadie!

10:47.990 --> 10:50.125
- Can't.
- No such word as "can't."

10:50.259 --> 10:52.928
Yes, there is, sir.
It's what the others call you.

10:53.062 --> 10:56.198
At least it sounds like "can't."

10:59.034 --> 11:00.035
Out.

11:00.169 --> 11:01.738
When you've changed,

11:01.870 --> 11:03.539
you can go
to the headmaster's office.

11:09.244 --> 11:11.213
Stop, sir. Stop, please.

11:12.848 --> 11:14.983
Why, McCreadie?

11:15.117 --> 11:17.086
You're tickling me, sir.

11:20.189 --> 11:23.392
- Greedy!
- You can fuck off.

11:23.525 --> 11:25.829
Things definitely got worse
when his dad died.

11:25.994 --> 11:29.198
I mean, it was like school
was some prison for him.

11:29.331 --> 11:30.265
<i>He was just...</i>

11:31.934 --> 11:34.536
<i>...you know,
waiting to bust out.</i>

11:36.372 --> 11:39.408
- We might have to sell the house.
- No. I can leave school.

11:39.541 --> 11:42.378
Use the money you spend on the
fees to pay for the mortgage.

11:42.511 --> 11:45.147
Your daddy wanted you
to have an education.

11:45.280 --> 11:46.850
He believed in education.

11:46.982 --> 11:51.053
He's not here now, is he?
He's in the car in front.

11:51.186 --> 11:53.355
I want you to be a success.

11:53.489 --> 11:55.924
I want you to go
to Oxford or Cambridge.

11:56.058 --> 11:58.660
I want you to be able to do
whatever you want to do.

11:58.927 --> 12:00.062
And I just wanna make money

12:00.195 --> 12:02.030
so I can do
whatever I want to do.

12:03.932 --> 12:06.468
<i>How did he get
the nickname "Greedy"?</i>

12:06.602 --> 12:08.303
<i>Greedy McCreadie.</i>

12:08.437 --> 12:09.873
<i>I mean, he chose the name.</i>

12:10.005 --> 12:11.073
<i>It was his gambling name.</i>

12:11.206 --> 12:12.941
- Ladies, Lewis.
- Piss off.

12:13.075 --> 12:15.477
- Right, <i>faites vos jeux.</i>
- What does that mean?

12:15.611 --> 12:18.113
It's French for
"place your fucking bets."

12:18.247 --> 12:20.249
<i>Cards was his thing.
Even back then,</i>

12:20.382 --> 12:23.352
<i>it was about gambling,
it was about making money.</i>

12:23.485 --> 12:24.453
Who's gonna get it?

12:27.156 --> 12:29.425
Okay, here we go.

12:29.558 --> 12:31.994
Oh, has he gone bust?
Ah, yes, he has.

12:32.127 --> 12:33.962
That's all mine.
Thank you very much.

12:34.096 --> 12:36.699
- McCreadie. Gambling?
- Lewis, thank you.

12:36.932 --> 12:38.500
How can it be gambling
when I always win?

12:38.634 --> 12:40.035
It is more like robbery.

12:40.169 --> 12:41.937
- Hand it over.
- Sir, what are you doing?

12:42.070 --> 12:43.939
Sir, no, no, no, no!
Sir, I'm the banker!

12:44.072 --> 12:45.875
- It is against school rules.
- It's my money.

12:46.008 --> 12:47.710
- No, this is mine.
- I'm confiscating it.

12:47.943 --> 12:49.879
What are you gonna do with it?
Buy a toothbrush?

12:50.012 --> 12:53.382
I'm gonna pay it to your mother
and watch her dance.

12:55.919 --> 12:58.922
I'm afraid at this school,
we expect the highest standards

12:59.054 --> 13:00.924
of behavior and achievement.

13:01.056 --> 13:03.927
Is that why you hit children?
Is that your high standard?

13:04.059 --> 13:06.161
Corporal punishment
is a necessary evil...

13:06.295 --> 13:10.165
You're an unnecessary evil, hm?

13:10.299 --> 13:11.868
Ricky,
let's get out of here.

13:12.000 --> 13:14.403
We don't need these people.
We don't need this school.

13:14.536 --> 13:17.306
I know your sort. You're
the sort that used to put up

13:17.439 --> 13:20.976
"no Irish, no blacks,
no dogs" signs, hm?

13:21.109 --> 13:23.746
I met plenty of people like you
when I came to London.

13:23.979 --> 13:26.348
Now look at me.
Take a good look.

13:26.482 --> 13:29.017
I've got much more money
than most of them have

13:29.151 --> 13:32.689
and a bloody sight
more than you.

13:36.124 --> 13:37.961
<i>Bye.</i>

13:39.394 --> 13:40.529
Goodbye, Mrs. McCreadie.

13:40.662 --> 13:43.432
The mother is worse
than the son.

13:43.565 --> 13:46.401
Bloody stuck-up English gits.

13:46.535 --> 13:49.271
- We're gonna show them.
- We are gonna be fine, Ricky.

13:49.404 --> 13:51.039
We'll be more than fine.

13:51.173 --> 13:53.041
Fuck them.

13:53.175 --> 13:54.944
Fuck all of them.

13:59.181 --> 14:02.551
- One more time. One more time.
- Oh, no, no.

14:02.685 --> 14:04.253
- Got it.
- It's simple.

14:04.386 --> 14:06.188
You know it's simple.
Follow the queen.

14:06.321 --> 14:07.456
Mm-hm.

14:08.524 --> 14:11.460
Watch... the... queen.

14:11.593 --> 14:13.428
Follow her like a corgi
humping her leg.

14:13.562 --> 14:16.398
- Right, Eric, where's the queen?
- Heh-heh. Hm...

14:16.532 --> 14:18.233
That one?

14:18.367 --> 14:20.536
Balls. Every time.
I don't know how you do it.

14:20.669 --> 14:22.104
- Eric!
- Come on, give me a fiver.

14:22.237 --> 14:23.505
I've gotta go see my supplier.

